No sheep, no need for thin stone barriers protecting vineyards. When you don't need path walls, it is logical to spare space by walking over stones removed in cultivation. This is the reason why these stone walls are so wide and easily spotted when viewed above.

If you’ve ever driven through coastal #Croatia, you might have noticed stone walls hugging hills and divvying up the countryside, some rock solid while others have crumbled into ruined mounds. They’re as much a part of Croatia’s coastal landscape as rugged hills, olive trees, and rocky coastline. So have you ever wondered, Why all the walls?
Called dry stone walls (suhozidovi or gromace), these structures were built without mortar to hold the stones in place. ­Instead, they were stacked and fit snugly together like puzzle pieces. The technique is centuries old – and so are most of the walls. Those dividing parcels of land on the Stari Grad Plain, one of Croatia’s seven UNESCO World Heritage Sites, were built as early as the 4th century BC.
